        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>fol.5.b.  I[ohn] D[ee]. Miror, cum ante, Ignem pro Eleme[n]to admittere no[n] vellet tamqu[am] generationi ineptum,
                    nunc ver&ograve; pro faecundissimo semine ponat, vnum h[abet] ex tribus primis, vnde cu[m] Eleme[n]ta [ipa.], tum Creatura[e] reliqua[e] o[mn]es
                    orr.centur <!--KS: 'orientur'?-->: sed sulphuris nome[n] minus offendisse in hoc loco sed vide [pagina[m]] [seque[n]tem].</marginalia_text> <!--JG: very uncertain-->
                    <person name="John Dee"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="NYSLWin188:00000024" text="5.b"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>I am amazed, when before, that he did not wish to admit fire for the element, as if inept for generation, now indeed he puts [it] for the most eloquent, he has one from the
                three prime,  hence both that element and all remaining creatures [...]: but the name of sulfur offended less in this place. But see the following page.
            </translation>
